05324nam a22008655i 9780231540216DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015003030  a(OCoLC)979742551  a97802315402167 a10.7312/chen173742doi  a(DE-B1597)468899  a(OCoLC)929851460  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aKNN440b.C4423 2016 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a349.51090332231 aChen, Li, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChinese Law in Imperial Eyes :bSovereignty, Justice, and Transcultural Politics /cLi Chen. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b18 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Imperial Archives and Historiography of Western Extraterritoriality in China -- t2. Translation of The Qing Code and Colonial Origins of Comparative Chinese Law -- t3. Chinese Law in The Formation of European Modernity -- t4. Sentimental Imperialism and The Global Spectacle of Chinese Punishments -- t5. Law and Empire in The Making of The First Opium War -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow did American schoolchildren, French philosophers, Russian Sinologists, Dutch merchants, and British lawyers imagine China and Chinese law? What happened when agents of presumably dominant Western empires had to endure the humiliations and anxieties of maintaining a profitable but precarious relationship with China? In Chinese Law in Imperial Eyes, Li Chen provides a richly textured analysis of these related issues and their intersection with law, culture, and politics in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.Using a wide array of sources, Chen's study focuses on the power dynamics of Sino-Western relations during the formative century before the First Opium War (1839-1842). He highlights the centrality of law to modern imperial ideology and politics and brings new insight to the origins of comparative Chinese law in the West, the First Opium War, and foreign extraterritoriality in China. The shifting balance of economic and political power formed and transformed knowledge of China and Chinese law in different contact zones. Chen argues that recovering the variegated and contradictory roles of Chinese law in Western "modernization" helps provincialize the subsequent Euro-Americentric discourse of global modernity.Chen draws attention to important yet underanalyzed sites in which imperial sovereignty, national identity, cultural tradition, or international law and order were defined and restructured. His valuable case studies show how constructed differences between societies were hardened into cultural or racial boundaries and then politicized to rationalize international conflicts and hierarchy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCriminal lawxChinaxHistory. 0aCriminal lawzChinaxHistory. 0aDa Qing lü. 0aExterritoriality. 0aExtraterritoriality. 0aJustice, Administration ofxChina. 0aJustice, Administration ofzChina. 0aLawxChinaxHistory. 0aLawxHistoryx18th centuryxChina. 0aLawxHistoryx19th centuryxChina. 0aLawzChinaxHistory. 0aSociological jurisprudencexChinaxHistory. 0aSociological jurisprudencexHistoryx18th centuryxChina. 0aSociological jurisprudencexHistoryx19th centuryxChina. 0aSociological jurisprudencezChinaxHistory. 0aSovereignty. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBo